\title{Threat Model Generation}

\taxon{skill}

\tag{security}

\tag{threat-model}

\tag{stride}

\meta{version}{1.0.0}

\meta{description}{Generate a STRIDE-based security threat model for a repository. Use when setting up security monitoring, after architecture changes, or for security audits.}

\subtree{
\title{Threat Model Generation}
\p{Generate a comprehensive security threat model for a repository using the STRIDE methodology. This skill analyzes the codebase architecture and produces an LLM-optimized threat model document that other security skills can reference.}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\ul{
\li{\strong{First-time setup} - New repository needs initial threat model}
\li{\strong{Architecture changes} - Significant changes to components, APIs, or data flows}
\li{\strong{Security audit} - Periodic review or compliance requirement}
\li{\strong{Manual request} - Security team requests updated threat model}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Inputs}
\p{Before running this skill, gather or confirm:}

\pre{\startverb
| Input                   | Description                                             | Required                         |
| ----------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Repository path         | Root directory to analyze                               | Yes (default: current directory) |
| Existing threat model   | Path to existing `.factory/threat-model.md` if updating | No                               |
| Compliance requirements | Frameworks to consider (SOC2, GDPR, HIPAA, etc.)        | No                               |
| Security contacts       | Email addresses for security team notifications         | No                               |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Instructions}
\p{Follow these steps in order:}

\subtree{
\title{Step 1: Analyze Repository Structure}
\p{Scan the codebase to understand the system:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Identify languages and frameworks}}
}

\ul{
\li{Check \code{\startverb package.json\stopverb}, \code{\startverb requirements.txt\stopverb}, \code{\startverb go.mod\stopverb}, \code{\startverb Cargo.toml\stopverb}, etc.}
\li{Note the primary tech stack (e.g., Next.js, Django, Go microservices)}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Map components and services}}
}

\ul{
\li{Look for \code{\startverb apps/\stopverb}, \code{\startverb services/\stopverb}, \code{\startverb packages/\stopverb} directories}
\li{Identify entry points: API routes, CLI commands, web handlers}
\li{Note databases, caches, message queues}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Identify external interfaces}}
}

\ul{
\li{HTTP endpoints (REST, GraphQL)}
\li{File upload handlers}
\li{Webhook receivers}
\li{OAuth/SSO integrations}
\li{CLI commands that accept user input}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Trace data flows}}
\li{How does user input enter the system?}
\li{Where is sensitive data stored?}
\li{What external services are called?}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 2: Identify Trust Boundaries}
\p{Define security zones:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Public Zone} (untrusted)}
}

\ul{
\li{All external HTTP endpoints}
\li{Public APIs without authentication}
\li{User-uploaded files}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Authenticated Zone} (partially trusted)}
}

\ul{
\li{Endpoints requiring valid session/token}
\li{User-specific data access}
\li{Rate-limited APIs}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Internal Zone} (trusted)}
\li{Service-to-service communication}
\li{Admin-only endpoints}
\li{Database connections}
\li{Secrets management}
}

\p{Document where trust boundaries exist and what validates transitions between zones.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 3: Inventory Critical Assets}
\p{Classify data by sensitivity:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{PII (Personally Identifiable Information)}}
}

\ul{
\li{User emails, names, addresses, phone numbers}
\li{Document protection measures}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Credentials & Secrets}}
}

\ul{
\li{Password hashes, API keys, OAuth tokens}
\li{JWT signing keys, encryption keys}
\li{Document rotation policies}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Business-Critical Data}}
\li{Transaction records, customer data}
\li{Proprietary algorithms, trade secrets}
\li{Document access controls}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 4: Apply STRIDE Analysis}
\p{For each major component, analyze threats in all six categories:}

\subtree{
\title{S - Spoofing Identity}
\ul{
\li{Can attackers impersonate users or services?}
\li{Are authentication mechanisms secure?}
\li{Look for: weak session handling, API key exposure, missing MFA}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{T - Tampering with Data}
\ul{
\li{Can attackers modify data in transit or at rest?}
\li{Look for: SQL injection, XSS, mass assignment, missing input validation}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{R - Repudiation}
\ul{
\li{Can users deny actions they performed?}
\li{Look for: missing audit logs, insufficient logging, no immutable trails}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{I - Information Disclosure}
\ul{
\li{Can attackers access data they shouldn't?}
\li{Look for: IDOR, verbose errors, hardcoded secrets, data leaks in logs}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{D - Denial of Service}
\ul{
\li{Can attackers disrupt service availability?}
\li{Look for: missing rate limits, resource exhaustion, algorithmic complexity}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{E - Elevation of Privilege}
\ul{
\li{Can attackers gain unauthorized access levels?}
\li{Look for: missing authorization checks, role manipulation, privilege escalation}
}

\p{For each identified threat:}

\ul{
\li{Describe the attack scenario}
\li{List vulnerable components}
\li{Show code patterns to look for}
\li{Note existing mitigations}
\li{Identify gaps}
\li{Assign severity (CRITICAL/HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW) and likelihood}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 5: Document Vulnerability Patterns}
\p{Create a library of code patterns specific to this codebase's tech stack:}

\pre{\startverb
# Example: SQL Injection patterns for Python
# VULNERABLE
sql = f"SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = {user_id}"

# SAFE
cursor.execute("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = ?", (user_id,))
\stopverb}

\p{Include patterns for:}

\ul{
\li{SQL injection}
\li{XSS (Cross-Site Scripting)}
\li{Command injection}
\li{Path traversal}
\li{Authentication bypass}
\li{IDOR (Insecure Direct Object Reference)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Step 6: Generate Output Files}
\p{Create two files:}

\subtree{
\title{1. \code{\startverb .factory/threat-model.md\stopverb}}
\p{Use the template in \code{\startverb stride-template.md\stopverb} to generate a comprehensive threat model with:}

\ul{
\li{System overview with architecture description}
\li{Trust boundaries and security zones}
\li{Attack surface inventory}
\li{Critical assets classification}
\li{STRIDE threat analysis for each component}
\li{Vulnerability pattern library}
\li{Security testing strategy}
\li{Assumptions and accepted risks}
\li{Version changelog}
}

\p{The document should be written in \strong{natural language} with code examples, optimized for LLM comprehension.}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. \code{\startverb .factory/security-config.json\stopverb}}
\p{Generate configuration metadata:}

\pre{\startverb
{
  "threat_model_version": "1.0.0",
  "last_updated": "<ISO timestamp>",
  "security_team_contacts": [],
  "compliance_requirements": [],
  "scan_frequency": "on_commit",
  "severity_thresholds": {
    "block_merge": ["CRITICAL"],
    "require_review": ["HIGH", "CRITICAL"],
    "notify_security_team": ["CRITICAL"]
  },
  "vulnerability_patterns": {
    "enabled": [
      "sql_injection",
      "xss",
      "command_injection",
      "path_traversal",
      "auth_bypass",
      "idor"
    ],
    "custom_patterns_path": null
  }
}
\stopverb}

\p{Customize based on:}

\ul{
\li{Detected compliance requirements (from docs, configs, or user input)}
\li{Security team contacts (if provided)}
\li{Tech stack (enable relevant vulnerability patterns)}
}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Success Criteria}
\p{The skill is complete when:}

\ul{
\li{[ ] \code{\startverb .factory/threat-model.md\stopverb} exists with all sections populated}
\li{[ ] \code{\startverb .factory/security-config.json\stopverb} exists with valid JSON}
\li{[ ] All major components have STRIDE analysis}
\li{[ ] Vulnerability patterns match the tech stack}
\li{[ ] Document is written in natural language (LLM-readable)}
\li{[ ] No placeholder text remains}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Verification}
\p{Run these checks before completing:}

\pre{\startverb
# Verify threat model exists and is non-empty
test -s .factory/threat-model.md && echo "✓ Threat model exists"

# Verify config is valid JSON
cat .factory/security-config.json | jq . > /dev/null && echo "✓ Config is valid JSON"

# Check threat model has key sections
grep -q "## 1. System Overview" .factory/threat-model.md && echo "✓ Has System Overview"
grep -q "## 5. Threat Analysis" .factory/threat-model.md && echo "✓ Has Threat Analysis"
grep -q "## 6. Vulnerability Pattern Library" .factory/threat-model.md && echo "✓ Has Pattern Library"
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example Invocations}
\p{\strong{Generate initial threat model:}}

\pre{\startverb
Generate a threat model for this repository using the threat-model-generation skill.
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Update existing threat model after architecture change:}}

\pre{\startverb
Update the threat model - we added a new payments service in services/payments/.
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Generate with compliance requirements:}}

\pre{\startverb
Generate a threat model for this repository. We need to comply with SOC2 and GDPR.
\stopverb}
}

